## 4. Template Alternates — Prefer These Over Editing Upstream Templates

Shopify supports **alternate templates** (`templates/product.r-*.json`). Use them instead of editing the upstream templates whenever a page needs a Rocky-specific layout.

```
templates/product.r-pdp.json      ← full Rocky PDP layout
templates/page.r-natural.json     ← "Natural" funnel page
templates/page.r-about.json       ← "About Us" page
templates/page.r-store-locator.json
templates/article.r-editorial.json
templates/collection.r-journal.json
```

**Never** add Rocky sections to `templates/product.json` or other upstream templates. If an upstream template must be changed (e.g. to add a section group or global block), register it in `.gitattributes` as `merge=ours` first.

Assign alternates to specific pages/products in the Shopify admin or via `config/settings_data.json`.

---

## 5. Modifying Upstream Files — Protocol

When touching an upstream file is genuinely the only path:

1. **Register in `.gitattributes` first:**
   ```
   sections/product-information.liquid merge=ours
   ```
2. **Add to the reference table** in `.cursor/references/gitattributes-merge-strategy.md`.
3. **Mark every Rocky addition** with an inline Liquid comment so they are easy to locate during upstream diffs:
   ```liquid
   {%- # r: tagline metafield added below product title -%}
   {% if product.metafields.rocky.tagline != blank %}
     <p class="r-product-tagline">{{ product.metafields.rocky.tagline }}</p>
   {% endif %}
   ```
   Use `{%- # r: ... -%}` — this is valid Liquid inline comment syntax.
4. During upstream updates, diff the upstream file against ours, cherry-pick any bug fixes, and preserve the `r:` marked additions.

---

## 6. Sections — Required Structure for `r-*` Files

### File Naming

```
sections/r-{area}-{descriptor}.liquid
```

Examples: `r-hero-campaign.liquid`, `r-pdp-routine-guide.liquid`, `r-journal-article.liquid`, `r-store-locator.liquid`

### Section Template

```liquid
{%- comment -%}
  Section: {Human name}
  Workstream: WS {N} — {Name}
  Description: {One-line purpose}
{%- endcomment -%}

<section
  id="{{ section.settings.custom_id | default: section.id }}"
  class="r-{name}"
  style="
    --r-{name}-pt: {{ section.settings.padding_top }}px;
    --r-{name}-pb: {{ section.settings.padding_bottom }}px;
  "
>
  <div class="r-page-width">
    {% content_for 'blocks' %}
  </div>
</section>

{% stylesheet %}
  .r-{name} {
    padding-block-start: var(--r-{name}-pt, 4rem);
    padding-block-end: var(--r-{name}-pb, 4rem);
  }
{% endstylesheet %}

{% schema %}
{
  "name": "t:names.r_{name}",
  "tag": "section",
  "blocks": [{ "type": "@theme" }, { "type": "@app" }],
  "settings": [
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_top",
      "label": "t:settings.padding_top",
      "min": 0, "max": 120, "step": 4, "default": 64, "unit": "px"
    },
    {
      "type": "range",
      "id": "padding_bottom",
      "label": "t:settings.padding_bottom",
      "min": 0, "max": 120, "step": 4, "default": 64, "unit": "px"
    }
  ],
  "presets": [{ "name": "t:names.r_{name}" }]
}
{% endschema %}
```

### Schema Translation Keys

Every Rocky section/block name and its setting labels must be added to `locales/en.default.schema.json`. Both locale files are `merge=ours`.

```json
{
  "names": {
    "r_journal_index": "Rocky — Journal Index",
    "r_hero_campaign": "Rocky — Hero Campaign"
  }
}
```

Always prefix the human-readable name with `Rocky — ` so Rocky sections group visually and alphabetically in the theme editor, clearly separate from upstream blocks.

---

## 7. Locale Keys — `rocky.*` Namespace

All Rocky storefront copy goes into `locales/en.default.json` under a top-level `rocky` namespace. Never mix Rocky keys into upstream namespaces.

```json
{
  "rocky": {
    "journal": {
      "read_more": "Read More",
      "back_to_journal": "Back to Journal"
    },
    "cart": {
      "rewards_bar_threshold": "You're {{ amount }} away from free shipping!"
    },
    "store_locator": {
      "find_store": "Find a Store",
      "my_store": "My Store"
    }
  }
}
```

Reference in Liquid:

```liquid
{{ 'rocky.journal.read_more' | t }}
```

---

## 8. Metafields and Metaobjects

All Rocky-specific metafield definitions must use the **`rocky`** namespace in Shopify admin. Reference them in Liquid as:

```liquid
{{ product.metafields.rocky.tagline }}
{{ product.metafields.rocky.routine_step }}
{{ article.metafields.rocky.campaign_issue }}
```

Metaobject definition names must be prefixed `rocky_`:

```
rocky_campaign_issue
rocky_store_location
rocky_ingredient
```

Never reuse or overwrite upstream metafield namespaces (e.g. `shopify.*`, `descriptors.*`).

---

## 9. Section Groups — Do Not Modify

`sections/header-group.json` and `sections/footer-group.json` are upstream files that control which sections appear in which editor zones. Do not modify them.

- Add Rocky header/footer variations through alternate templates or by composing Rocky sections inside the existing header/footer sections using `{% content_for 'blocks' %}`.
- If a new section group is genuinely required, create `sections/r-{name}-group.json` and register it in `layout/theme.liquid` via `{% sections 'r-{name}-group' %}` (which is already `merge=ours`).

---

## 10. App Integrations (Loop, Judge.me, Klaviyo)

When embedding third-party app functionality:

- **Use app blocks** (`{ "type": "@app" }` in section schemas) within Rocky sections — never embed app JS/Liquid snippets directly into upstream files.
- **Loop Subscription Widget:** Render inside `r-pdp-buy-button.liquid` or equivalent Rocky block. Custom CSS lives in the section's `{% stylesheet %}` to override Loop's default styles to match Horizon tokens.
- **Judge.me:** Use as app blocks within `r-pdp-social-proof.liquid`. Never add Judge.me render tags to upstream `sections/product-information.liquid` unless unavoidable (if so, use the upstream modification protocol in §5).
- **Klaviyo:** Add Klaviyo form app blocks to Rocky sections. Script loading (if required globally) goes in `snippets/scripts.liquid` — which is **not** currently in `.gitattributes`, so register it there first.

---

## 11. JavaScript — Rocky JS Stays Separate

Rocky JS lives in `assets/r-*.js`. Never add Rocky code to upstream asset files.

Load it from within the section or layout that needs it:

```liquid
{{- 'r-store-locator.js' | asset_url | script_tag -}}
```

Or deferred for below-fold content:

```html
<script src="{{ 'r-journal.js' | asset_url }}" defer></script>
```

**Custom elements** must use the `r-` prefix:

```js
// assets/r-store-locator.js
import { Component } from '@theme/component';

class StoreLocator extends Component {
  // ...
}

customElements.define('r-store-locator', StoreLocator);
```

Follow all rules in `javascript-standards.mdc`: `Component` framework, no `console.log` in production, async/await, JSDoc types.

---

## 12. Upstream Update Protocol

When Shopify releases a new Horizon version:

1. **Create a staging branch** — pull upstream into it, never directly into the working branch.
2. **Diff all `merge=ours` files** against the new upstream versions:
   - Cherry-pick upstream bug fixes into our versions of those files.
   - Look for new schema settings, new snippet utilities, new JS patterns worth adopting.
3. **Audit `{%- # r: ... -%}` markers** in any upstream file we touched — ensure Rocky additions survive and still make sense against the new upstream code.
4. **Pull in non-conflicting files freely** — any upstream file we have not customised (not in `.gitattributes`) can be accepted as-is.
5. **Test in a development/preview theme** via `shopify theme dev` or a duplicate theme before merging to main.
6. **Update `.gitattributes`** if new files were customized during this cycle.

---

## 13. Deploy Discipline

- **Never push directly to the live theme** during active development. Use `shopify theme dev` for local preview, or duplicate the theme in the Shopify admin and push to the copy.
- Use `shopify theme push --development` to push to the development theme.
- Gate production pushes behind at least one full cross-browser review on a preview theme.

