## 14. Colour Schemes

### How the Horizon Scheme System Works

Horizon's colour system is **context-driven via CSS custom properties**. Understanding this is essential before writing any colour-related code.

1. `config/settings_data.json` stores the palette for every scheme under `color_schemes`.
2. `snippets/color-schemes.liquid` loops over them at render time and emits a scoped CSS block for each:
   ```css
   :root, .color-scheme-1 { --color-background: #fff; --color-foreground: …; /* ~35 tokens */ }
   .color-scheme-2         { --color-background: #f5f5f5; … }
   .color-scheme-3         { --color-background: #1c1c1c; … }
   ```
   The **first scheme** also applies to `:root` — making it the global page default.
3. A section applies a scheme by adding `color-{{ section.settings.color_scheme }}` to its root element's class. Every descendant — buttons, inputs, swatches, prices — automatically inherits the right tokens via CSS cascade.
4. Upstream components **only ever reference semantic tokens** (`var(--color-background)`, `var(--color-foreground)`, `var(--color-primary)`, etc.) — never raw colour values.

### Rocky's Scheme Strategy: 3 Schemes, Repurpose the First 3 IDs

Rocky uses exactly **3 colour schemes**. Rather than creating new IDs, repurpose `scheme-1`, `scheme-2`, and `scheme-3` with Rocky's palette. Keeping the existing IDs ensures all upstream section defaults (`"default": "scheme-1"` etc.) remain valid with zero changes.

| Scheme ID | Rocky name | Intended use |
|---|---|---|
| `scheme-1` | **Rocky Light** | Primary surface — white/clean, main commerce pages |
| `scheme-2` | **Rocky Dark** | Inverse — hero sections, feature callouts, dark bars |
| `scheme-3` | **Rocky Journal** | Editorial — warm off-white/natural, Journal mode surfaces |

Configure these colour values in the Shopify admin Theme Editor (Settings → Colours). The values are saved to `config/settings_data.json`, which is `merge=ours`.

**Remove schemes 4–6** from `settings_data.json` — they add noise to the theme editor and are not needed. Any upstream section preset that references `scheme-4` or higher will fall back to the `:root` default (`scheme-1`).

### Applying Schemes in Rocky Sections

Scheme support is identical for `r-*` sections and upstream sections:

**Schema setting** (add to every section that supports scheme switching):
```json
{
  "type": "color_scheme",
  "id": "color_scheme",
  "label": "t:settings.color_scheme",
  "default": "scheme-1"
}
```

**Root element class**:
```liquid
<section
  class="r-hero-campaign color-{{ section.settings.color_scheme }}"
  …
>
```

Child elements use upstream tokens — no Rocky-specific tokens needed for standard colour roles:
```css
.r-hero-campaign__title  { color: var(--color-foreground-heading); }
.r-hero-campaign__body   { color: var(--color-foreground); }
.r-hero-campaign         { background: var(--color-background); }
```

### Extending Schemes with Rocky-Specific Tokens

Horizon's ~35 tokens cover standard commerce UI. Rocky surfaces (Journal editorial, brand Canmore tan, etc.) need additional tokens that have no upstream equivalent. Do **not** add these to `settings_schema.json` — that is an upstream file.

Instead, hang them off the same `.color-scheme-*` class in `assets/r-base.css`. This keeps them in sync with whichever scheme is active:

```css
/* r-base.css */

/* Rocky Light (scheme-1) */
.color-scheme-1 {
  --r-surface-subtle:      #f8f6f2;
  --r-color-journal-bg:   #f5f0e8;
  --r-color-brand-accent:  #c4a882; /* Canmore tan */
  --r-color-brand-primary: #2b2b2b;
}

/* Rocky Dark (scheme-2) */
.color-scheme-2 {
  --r-surface-subtle:      #1a1a1a;
  --r-color-journal-bg:   #201e1b;
  --r-color-brand-accent:  #d4b892;
  --r-color-brand-primary: #f5f5f5;
}

/* Rocky Journal (scheme-3) */
.color-scheme-3 {
  --r-surface-subtle:      #ede8df;
  --r-color-journal-bg:   #e8e0d3;
  --r-color-brand-accent:  #8b6a45;
  --r-color-brand-primary: #1c1c1c;
}
```

Rocky sections then consume these alongside upstream tokens:
```css
.r-journal-card {
  background: var(--r-color-journal-bg);  /* Rocky-specific */
  color: var(--color-foreground);          /* Upstream token  */
  border-color: var(--color-border);       /* Upstream token  */
}
```

### Rules for Colour in Rocky Components

- **Always use tokens, never raw hex values** in `{% stylesheet %}` or `r-base.css`
- **Use upstream tokens first** — only reach for `--r-*` tokens when there is no upstream equivalent
- **Never define `--color-*` custom properties** (upstream namespace) in Rocky files — that would silently override upstream tokens
- **Rocky-specific extra tokens must be scoped to `.color-scheme-*` classes** in `r-base.css`, not `:root`, so they stay in sync with the active scheme
- **Scheme-independent brand tokens** (e.g. a fixed logo colour that never changes with scheme) are the only `--r-*` values that belong on `:root` in `r-base.css`

### Scheme Inheritance in Nested Blocks

Horizon blocks support `inherit_color_scheme`. When a block's `inherit_color_scheme` is `true`, it takes the colour context from its parent section. Rocky blocks should follow the same pattern:

```json
{
  "type": "checkbox",
  "id": "inherit_color_scheme",
  "label": "t:settings.inherit_color_scheme",
  "default": true
},
{
  "type": "color_scheme",
  "id": "color_scheme",
  "label": "t:settings.color_scheme",
  "default": "scheme-1",
  "visible_if": "{{ block.settings.inherit_color_scheme == false }}"
}
```

```liquid
<div
  class="r-my-block{% unless block.settings.inherit_color_scheme %} color-{{ block.settings.color_scheme }}{% endunless %}"
  …
>
```

